post_text:
They went, they worked, they succeeded! 17 archers, one goal!

CONGRATULATIONS!! Wilton Miner Archery has earned the title of 2019 Western National 3-D Elementary CHAMPIONS!! Miner archery also took home SECOND place elementary division in Western National Bullseye competition.

Everyone did a remarkable job working together and supporting one another to achieve this honor.

Great job to all the Wilton Minor Archers in an extremely successful 2019 archery season. We are proud to be your coaches and watch your successes in this wonderful sport! The best is truly yet to come for our team. GO MINER ARCHERY ~ Coach Caitlyn & Coach Ell

shared_text:
North Dakota Game and Fish Department
March 18 at 5:59 AM ·

NASP State Tournament Canceled: Following the announced week-long closure of North Dakota's K-12 schools, the National Archery in the Schools Program state tournament scheduled for this weekend in Minot has been canceled due to public health concerns.

With an estimated 1,000 archers in grades 4-12 expected to convene Friday, March 20 at the State Fair Center, the North Dakota Game and Fish Department is following the recommendation of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that groups cancel or postpone in-person events that consist of 50 people or more.
text:
North Dakota Game and Fish Department
March 18 at 5:59 AM ·

NASP State Tournament Canceled: Following the announced week-long closure of North Dakota's K-12 schools, the National Archery in the Schools Program state tournament scheduled for this weekend in Minot has been canceled due to public health concerns.

With an estimated 1,000 archers in grades 4-12 expected to convene Friday, March 20 at the State Fair Center, the North Dakota Game and Fish Department is following the recommendation of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that groups cancel or postpone in-person events that consist of 50 people or more.

post_text:
We understand the frustration and disappointment that canceling the state competition has caused. At this time of uncertainty across the nation, we want to thank the ND State NASP coordinator for putting the archers and spectators first in making this difficult decision to cancel the ND State Archery Tournament.

Archers: We want to let you know how very proud we are of each and every one of you. You came to practice excited to be part of the Miner program, improving your skills and encouraging one another throughout the year. Your dedication to the program is something that we are very proud of.

Thank you, parents and supporters, for making the 2019-2020 archery season successful. As this season did not end how we would have liked, we must remember that it is for the best interest of the health and safety of everyone.

As information becomes available, it will be shared. Thank you ~~~ Coach Bob, Coach Emily, Coach Caitlyn

post_text: Yesterday, Miner Archery traveled to Cooperstown for both 3-D and Bullseye. They awarded the top three spots. Wilton did not bring home any awards; however, we did have many that would have placed in the top 10. Competition is increasing, and this is a good way to gauge how we compete with other top competition from across the state. It is not always about bringing home medals, it is about improving each week and learning what we can do to be better. I am extremely proud of how Miner Archery performed yesterday and know we will only get better in the next few weeks of competition leading into State. Stay healthy, keep those grades up, and lets work on being the best we can be! Go Miner Archery!

post_text:
Our Middle & High School Miner archers combined to create one Miner High School team. The archers did an amazing job with a combined score of 3207 placing sixth place out of 10 teams!!!! This was a fantastic score as this was the first time Miner Archery was able to put a high school team into competition. With a lot of younger archers in the middle school bracket our team will improve and will be on a top contender list in the years to come!! Our team is young and eager to take these awards home. Let's keep it up Miners!
**Here is a picture of our entire 2018-2019 team who attended the 2019 ND NASP State Tournament. Way to go Miner Archery!

Archery is a pretty amazing sport that awards excellence each year to pay for future education.

post_text:
A lot more personal best scores today. Competition is increasing and scores are going up. Keep focused on each arrow and remember what we go over at practice, breath, relax and aim. Don’t worry about how everyone else shoots or how fast they get their arrows shot, but how YOU can improve YOURSELF. Shoot at tournaments how you shoot at practice, do not change your habits.

Rest up and keep shooting next week on your own. Practices begin the first full week of March. We will begin to prepare for state and our practices become slightly different and more focused to fine tune our aiming, breathing, and focusing. Its go time Miner Archery, let’s show everyone what we got! Coach Ell & Coach Caitlyn

Miner Archery met some top notch competition today at Gackle. This is about what to expect in regards to scores at the state competition. 13 hours, 3 tournaments, 309 miles, hundreds of laughs, and a whole lot of experience gained!! What a LONG day, but we could not be any more proud of our archers and fan base supporting us! The parents support is amazing, and the lunches packed were terrific (thank you again volunteers for coordinating, that saved us a lot of time).
Everyone shot great and several improved their personal best scores! We are so proud of each and every one of you and how you are improving. Rest up and stay healthy as next weekend is our own Miner Archery Tournament! Let’s show them how it is done in Wilton! Go Miner Archery!!! ~~Coach Ell & Coach Caitlyn
**And cheer for Coach Caitlyn who is, OBVIOUSLY, your favorite coach at our second annual coach off!!!

post_text:
To all the Wilton Miner Archers…..I want you to know how very proud coach Caitlyn & myself are of EVERY ONE of you. It is not about bringing home a medal or taking home a trophy. Archery is about how YOU improve. With ANY sport you know you will have your good days and your bad days. Not every day will be great, but every day you learn something. If you came home defeated or not feeling good about yourself, DON’T. If you truly enjoy the sport (any sport), don’t give up, just dig deep and become the best person YOU can be and just practice, practice, and then practice some more.

If today was your last archery shoot, be proud of how you did and how far you have come as an archer, and as an individual. Look back at the good times and remember why you joined to begin with. Not for a medal, trophy, or a trip, but because you simply ENJOY the sport. I hope to see you back next year as we continue to work together as a team and we all improve and learn together. ~~coach Ell

post_text:
All State Team and Recognition

The North Dakota Youth Archery Advisory Committee created a new designation starting in 2016/17 to recognize student archers who had excelled throughout the regional archery tournament season.

To qualify for this honor, student archers must participate in a North Dakota NASP regulated regional tournament and achieve the following scores:

Elementary (Grades 3-5) – 240 points or higher
Middle School (Grades 6-8) – 270 points or higher
High School (Grades 9-12) – 275 points or higher

• The top twelve student archer scores (regardless of gender) in each division will receive the designation as a member of the North Dakota All State Archery Team.

• If more than 12 archers qualify there will be a round of 5 arrows at 15 meters for practice, followed by 5 arrows for score. Should a tie occur there will be a shoot-off at the state tournament; each archer shoots 1 arrow, closest to center wins. Archer must participate in the state tournament to be able to qualify for the shoot out.

Yesterday we met some tough competition when we traveled to Gackle. This will be about where scores will be for state next month as some of the top competition from ND competed at this tournament. We’re proud of each one of our Miner archers as this was an intimidating day with some very big numbers produced from archers from across North Dakota. This was a good thing to go and compete and see how we compare to other schools across ND that will be competing in the state tournament. Today was productive and everyone will be in a better place to prepare for the next two tournaments (Medina & Rolla), as well as the State tournament in March.

Rest up archers, next week we travel to Medina. Coach Caitlyn and myself will be making adjustments to our normal practice to better prepare ourselves for next weeks tournament guidelines (9m, 12m). We will be ready and prepared to compete as individuals and as teams!! Come prepared to better ourselves and encourage one other. GO MINER ARCHERY! ~~ Coach Caitlyn & Coach Ell

post_text:
We would like to thank all the parents, community members, school staff, and archers who helped make this tournament a huge success.

This tournament would never have happened without the support of each one of you that helped set up, work in concessions, line judge, work registration, helped score, prepare and serve the food in the kitchen, clean up everywhere, and just step in where you saw an extra set of hands were needed.

We (Caitie and myself) were able to coach and be the tournament official knowing things were handled all around us, which we cannot say thank you enough. We are truly humbled by the show of support for the Wilton Miner Archery program. Thank you for everything you do to make this program successful~~Coach Ell & Coach Caitlyn

post_text: Yesterday, 29 Miner archers, two coaches, and one brave chaperone boarded the bus and traveled 416 miles to compete at Cooperstown & Edgeley tournaments. We had a fantastic group of parents that came to support the archers at the tournaments, braving the cold and snow. Thank you to those who coordinated the lunch for the archers and for those who helped haul bows so the archers weren’t cramped on the bus. It was an amazing experience for both the archers and coaches. Everyone kept a positive attitude and shot wonderfully. The scores that the Miner Archers produced were terrific. Thank you archers and parents for making this two tournaments/one day a great experience. Enjoy your much needed break….and we will see you all on Wednesday for practice (all grades 3:30-5:00) as we prepare for our tournament next Saturday. Way to go Miner Archery, we are SO PROUD OF EACH ONE OF YOU!! Coach Ell & Coach Caitlyn

These products will be available on Friday, February 2 at County Line Café’. Thank you for your generosity in helping our program!!

January 31, 2018 at 9:53 AM ·

On Friday at the County Line at the Sip and Shop I will have some bath bombs with these little charms in them! The proceeds of the sales from these Bath Bombs will go to the Wilton Archery Team! We also have some shower steamers and salt cakes in purple and gold bags that we are selling and the proceeds from that will go to the archery and cheer team! You can also order them at any time by messaging me. They have such an amazing team! It’s great to see the kids doing a sport that dates so far back in history! It would only seem appropriate that with a name like Valhalla’s Haze that we would be cheering on the archery team now wouldn’t it!?!? 😉🏹🏹🏹🏹🏹🏹 Kelly Erlandson

post_text:
Archers: Looking at scoring reports everyone did very well. Even if you were within a few points from last tournament, that is okay. We only expect you to try your best. Do not worry about how everyone else shot or how everyone else is doing. You be the best YOU can be. The only person you are in competition with is yourself. Remember…when you step up to that line you are the only one you are shooting against. It doesn’t matter who is on the same bale as you, you compete against yourself…one arrow at a time.

We are proud of how each one shot today! Rest up archers, next week we show two towns what we have……..Two tournaments, One day…Let’s go Miner Archery!
~~Coach Ell & Coach Caitlyn

post_text: Wilton Miner Archers: We are extremely impressed how each one of you shot! It isn’t about going home with a medal, it is about IMPROVING. Your homework is to write down your scores you shot today. Your personal goal will be to maintain or IMPROVE your score at each tournament. You all did great and now everyone has the first time tournament jitters out of the way, we can start to work on improving. Get some sleep, enjoy your day off tomorrow , and Monday we will start working to get ready for our next tournament, January 27 at Kensal. We are proud of EACH ONE OF YOU! GO MINERS!! Coach Ell & Coach Cailtyn

post_text: For those of you attending the state fair this Thursday and Friday, swing by the ND Game & Fish area. You just might see last years captain, and newly certified NASP instructor, Caitlyn Ell, helping future archers. Archery doesn't end when you graduate, it is a truly a life-long sport! Aim high Miner Archers, 2017-2018 is looking to be more exciting than ever!

post_text: Pics of our dunking booth is featured in the Leader News! Thank you again to our sponsors, parent and community volunteers that helped, our brave participants that agreed to get dunked, and of course to everyone that came to support the Miner Archery program.
shared_text:
Leader-News
June 22, 2017 at 1:57 PM ·

Rain wasn't the only thing splashing at this weekend's Wild In Wilton. Community members and McLean County deputies took turns in the hot seat Saturday as adults and children had target practice at the Wilton Archery dunking booth.

More photos in this week's Leader-News!

post_text: Brad Nielsen...you are the winner of the $20 gift certificate to Sportsmen's Bar & Grill for getting most dunked! Congratulations and thank you for getting DUNKED the most! You have a great fan club willing to come and support your endeavors!! :)
